    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2814570926" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2814570926" />
    <a title="Celia Buell" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29892659-celia-buell"><img alt="Celia Buell" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1550789566p2/29892659.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2814570926?book_show_action=true">Jun 28, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Celia Buell" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Celia Buell" href="/user/show/29892659-celia-buell">Celia Buell</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29892659-celia-buell?shelf=owned">owned</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29892659-celia-buell?shelf=under-350-pages">under-350-pages</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29892659-celia-buell?shelf=print-copy">print-copy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29892659-celia-buell?shelf=nbrc-tower-teams">nbrc-tower-teams</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29892659-celia-buell?shelf=floab-pirates">floab-pirates</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2814570926" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15683348531063215624">This is the kind of book I didn&apos;t think I would get into, because it started off slow and had an overly poetic style that is difficult to draw you in as a novel itself. In some ways a slice of life story and in some ways literary fiction akin to <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/35959740.Circe' title='Circe by Madeline Miller' rel='nofollow noopener'>Circe</a> with its own stories that converge in unexpected way, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/51589.Chitra_Banerjee_Divakaruni' title='Chitra Banerjee Divakaruni' rel='nofollow noopener'>Chitra Banerjee Divakaruni</a> brings a unique voice to literary adult fiction.<br/><br/>As I said, this was difficult to get into because of all the stories that seemed at first not to converge into anything</span>
  <span id="freeText15683348531063215624" style="display:none">This is the kind of book I didn't think I would get into, because it started off slow and had an overly poetic style that is difficult to draw you in as a novel itself. In some ways a slice of life story and in some ways literary fiction akin to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/35959740.Circe" title="Circe by Madeline Miller" rel="nofollow noopener">Circe</a> with its own stories that converge in unexpected way, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/51589.Chitra_Banerjee_Divakaruni" title="Chitra Banerjee Divakaruni" rel="nofollow noopener">Chitra Banerjee Divakaruni</a> brings a unique voice to literary adult fiction.<br /><br />As I said, this was difficult to get into because of all the stories that seemed at first not to converge into anything particularly novel-like. I've also had less than stellar experiences with a lot of adult literary fiction, especially when it comes to romance. However, the character of Tilo is well-written in a way that deals with real issues and makes her a real person without being over the top. In the same vein, this is not overly fantasy or romance or any one genre. It is a fully human story.<br /><br />In a way, this makes the magic almost believable. I really like the idea of a subtle magic community under the surface of the world we live in. Not something like Harry Potter, where the story is set in the real world but all about the magic, but a story that embodies the meaning of magical realism with magic both known and unknown to a community, a large city even. In many ways, this is a story of the human condition; of what it means to love and care and be a member of a community, or of multiple communities, and yet to still question your place.<br /><br />In terms of the writing itself, Divakaruni makes some interesting choices in terms of punctuation. While the novel is primarily in the first person perspective of Tilo, sometimes she slips into her life from an observer's point of view, in third person and occasionally even in second. I generally find novels that switch POV centering around the same, single person to be hard to follow, but again I felt this was done with intention in a way that manages to blend the genres. I also found it interesting that when she asks questions in the first person POV of her thoughts, she never uses a question mark and instead a period. This adds to the poetic nature of the novel.<br /><br />Overall I'm surprised at how much I enjoyed this given its low reviews. I can definitely see myself returning to this and learning something new with a reread, as well as recommending it to a wide variety of people and interests. On the other hand, I can see how some find it a little slow, and at the same time others might say it's too much of what it is. For me, though, it's a well-written blend of many of the elements I look for in a novel.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15683348531063215624" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


